Matthew,

Thanks for taking the time to respond and for sharing your
expertise.  Your question is exactly why I am seeking advice.

I guess a fundamental question is why would I choose a blog as
opposed to a website?  I am not married to either idea but just
wondering what to go with first, why, and how much work would it be
to retrofit if I decide to move to the other at some time in the
future.

One thing I am not clear about is what I call the topography of the
podcast layout.

Here is my thinking:

1. I would use the blog for interaction with listeners.

2. The website would contain a menu of casts and a one or two
sentence description of each show along with some relatively static
information - background, bio.  This site would also have links to
archived shows.  The website would link to the blog and to other
blogs/sites of similar interest.

3.  The blog would have a link to the website if someone is more
curious about the show.

4.  The blog would also have a menu of shows but with just a one to
three word descriptive title for each.  The blog would also contain a
link to the archives mentioned above.

5.  I would publish each new show to both the blog and website.

As I type this it does sound overcomplicated.
What do you think?

Thanks again for your help.

Jerry

