:-)  You hit on it.

I believe it's a "best practice" that we make our users do as little
work as possible to get and interact with our content. Because there
are so many choices for a listener, they will naturally gravitate to
those sites / podcasts that are easiest to use.

So!

With WordPress (especially with the PodPress plugin) there is no
reason to have more than one website.

WordPress uses Categories to organize your site.  It's very easy to
create a category called "Podcasts," for example, and use the feed to
that category as your podcast-only feed.  Your podcast is, in truth,
just a blog post with a media file attached -- by putting all the
podcast posts in the same category, you eliminate the need to have a
different solution for blog and podcast.   Does that make sense?

You can take a look at my personal site, which servers many purposes
-- including hosting my occasional personal podcast, Sonitotum.

This is a WordPress site.  The RSS feed for my blog (not my podcast) is
http://www.mattselznick.com/scribtotum/?feed=rss2
The RSS feed for Sonitotum (the podcast -- technically part of the blog) is
http://www.mattselznick.com/scribtotum/category/new-media/podcasts/so...

One site, with blog, podcast, static pages, and more -- and one stop
for my users.

Lots of folks on this list use a similar set-up... and I've helped
many clients set things up like this, as well.  Contact me off-list if
you'd like to contract me for direct help... and feel free to keep the
questions coming here on the list, as well!

